¿Qué cosas pueden causar un fallback a React.lazy?

React.lazy is used to dynamically import components in your application, and it can be useful when you need to load components asynchronously. However, if an error occurs during the lazy loading process, a fallback component will be displayed instead of the loaded component.

The most common cause for this fallback behavior is a syntax error or a missing dependency in one of the imported modules. For example:

import React from 'react';
const Component = () => {
  return <h1>Hello World!</h1>;
};
export default React.lazy(() => import('./Component'));

In this case, if there is an error in the file './Component.js', the fallback component will be displayed instead of the loaded component.

Another common cause for a fallback to React.lazy is a missing dependency. For example:

import React from 'react';
const Component = () => {
  return <h1>Hello World!</h1>;
};
export default React.lazy(() => import('./Component'));

In this case, if there are no dependencies in the file './Component.js', the fallback component will be displayed instead of the loaded component.

To avoid a fallback to React.lazy, make sure that you have all necessary imports and dependencies. Also, check for syntax errors or other issues in your code that could cause an error during lazy loading.

